sus applying runtime settings immediately and then restarting for the journal compression config. The ConfigMap approach is cleaner and keeps all settings in one place, so I'll go with that.\n\nMy plan is to create a ConfigMap containing the mongod.conf file with the necessary settings for log verbosity, slow operation threshold, and journal compression...\n\nWriting config file...\n\nThe StatefulSet update will automatically trigger a rolling restart since it's already configured with RollingUpdate strategy and maxUnavailable set to 1, which means we'll maintain availability with at least 4 of the 5 replica members running at any time.\n\nI notice the current manifest doesn't actually have authentication enabled at the mongod level despite the task mentioning it—there's no --auth flag and the keyfile secret isn't mounted—so I'll skip adding auth configuration and just focus on the three observability and storage settings requested. I'm also considering whether changing the journal compression will affect the existing persistent volumes, but since we're doing a rolling update, each pod will handle the transition as it restarts. I'll leave auth disabled to avoid breaking existing connections, and focus on adding just the three required configuration settings. My plan is to create a ConfigMap with the mongod configuration file, apply it, then patch the StatefulSet to mount it and use the `--config` flag instead of individual command-line arguments.\n\nWriting mongod.conf... I need to add a ConfigMap volume and mount it in the container, then do a rolling restart to apply the journal compression change. The log level and slowms updates can happen immediately through `setParameter`, but the journal compression requires a restart since WiredTiger needs to pick up that new setting. I'm also reconsidering the auth setup—the StatefulSet doesn't currently have `--auth` or `--keyFile` flags enabled, so even though secrets exist, authentication isn't actually enforced on the running replica set.\n\nLooking at the rolling update strategy with maxUnavailable: 1, the pods will restart one at a time from highest to lowest ordinal, each rejoining the replica set as it comes back up.\n\nSince we have 5 members with a quorum of 3, the cluster stays available throughout. When the primary restarts, a secondary will take over automatically.\n\nMy approach is to update the ConfigMap with the new mongod.conf, then patch the StatefulSet to mount it and use the new command, which will trigger the rolling restart. After monitoring the restart completes, I'll verify the settings are applied across all members.\n\nI'm also considering the auth requirement - the task mentions auth is enabled, so I need to make sure I don't break any existing auth configuration while making these changes.\n\nNow I'm putting together the final mongod.conf file with the logging, profiling, storage compression, and network binding settings.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2810,"cache_read_input_tokens":33845,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2810},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8ba6d5db-1ac5-4c28-8326-4ae383d3bf4f","uuid":"66d78c4c-9519-416b-a68e-54b2928023ed","request_id":"req_011Cc4xgHWe7a86J6LsvZVGk"}
